1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"1187–":"1187–Overleden","1187–Male":"1187–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1160–Male":"1160–Overleden","1162–Female":"1162–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1187–":"1187–Deceased","1187–Male":"1187–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":72,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Fowke was born in 1187, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, his father, Marmaduke Fowke, was 28 and his mother, Mabella Cole, was 25. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1187–":"1187–Surnud","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","Brewood, Staffordshire, England